President Donald J. Trump has declared a major disaster in the State of Minnesota and authorized Federal assistance to aid in recovery efforts following severe storms, tornadoes, straight-line winds, and flooding that occurred from June 15 to July 11, 2018. This assistance will supplement State, Tribal, and local recovery efforts in the affected areas. Federal funding will be available to State and Tribal governments, eligible local governments, and certain nonprofit organizations on a cost-sharing basis for emergency work and the repair or replacement of damaged facilities. The counties and tribes eligible for assistance include Aitkin, Beltrami, Blue Earth, Brown, Carlton, Cass, Clearwater, Cottonwood, Faribault, Itasca, Jackson, Koochiching, Lake, Lyon, Martin, Murray, Nicollet, Nobles, Pine, Pipestone, Polk, Redwood, Renville, Rock, St. Louis, Sibley, and Watonwan. Hazard mitigation measures statewide are also eligible for funding. Steven W. Johnson has been named the Federal Coordinating Officer for Federal recovery operations in the affected areas. Additional designations may be made in the future based on further damage assessments. For more information, media can contact the FEMA News Desk at (202) 646-3272 or FEMA-NEWS-DESK@FEMA.DHS.GOV.